<doc id="39382" wikidata="Q17502105" url="?curid=39382" title="Infimum and supremum">
<text>In mathematics, the infimum (abbreviated inf; : infima) of a subset formula_1 of a partially ordered set formula_2 is the greatest element in formula_2 that is less than or equal to each element of formula_4 if such an element exists. If the infimum of formula_1 exists, it is unique, and if &quot;b&quot; is a lower bound of formula_1, then &quot;b&quot; is less than or equal to the infimum of formula_1. Consequently, the term &quot;greatest lower bound&quot; (abbreviated as ) is also commonly used. The supremum (abbreviated sup; : suprema) of a subset formula_1 of a partially ordered set formula_2 is the least element in formula_2 that is greater than or equal to each element of formula_4 if such an element exists. If the supremum of formula_1 exists, it is unique, and if &quot;b&quot; is an upper bound of formula_1, then the supremum of formula_1 is less than or equal to &quot;b&quot;. Consequently, the supremum is also referred to as the &quot;least upper bound&quot; (or ).

The infimum is, in a precise sense, dual to the concept of a supremum. Infima and suprema of real numbers are common special cases that are important in analysis, and especially in Lebesgue integration. However, the general definitions remain valid in the more abstract setting of order theory where arbitrary partially ordered sets are considered.

The concepts of infimum and supremum are close to minimum and maximum, but are more useful in analysis because they better characterize special sets which may have . For instance, the set of positive real numbers formula_15 (not including formula_16) does not have a minimum, because any given element of formula_15 could simply be divided in half resulting in a smaller number that is still in formula_18 There is, however, exactly one infimum of the positive real numbers relative to the real numbers: formula_19 which is smaller than all the positive real numbers and greater than any other real number which could be used as a lower bound. An infimum of a set is always and only defined relative to a superset of the set in question. For example, there is no infimum of the positive real numbers inside the positive real numbers (as their own superset), nor any infimum of the positive real numbers inside the complex numbers with positive real part.

== Formal definition ==
A of a subset formula_1 of a partially ordered set formula_21 is an element formula_22 of formula_2 such that
* formula_24 for all formula_25 
A lower bound formula_26 of formula_1 is called an (or , or ) of formula_1 if
* for all lower bounds formula_22 of formula_1 in formula_31 formula_32 (formula_26 is larger than any other lower bound).

Similarly, an of a subset formula_1 of a partially ordered set formula_21 is an element formula_36 of formula_2 such that
* formula_38 for all formula_25 
An upper bound formula_40 of formula_1 is called a (or , or ) of formula_1 if
* for all upper bounds formula_36 of formula_1 in formula_31 formula_46 (formula_40 is less than any other upper bound).

== Existence and uniqueness ==

Infima and suprema do not necessarily exist. Existence of an infimum of a subset formula_1 of formula_2 can fail if formula_1 has no lower bound at all, or if the set of lower bounds does not contain a greatest element. (An example of this is the subset formula_51 of formula_52. It has upper bounds, such as 1.5, but no supremum in formula_52.)

Consequently, partially ordered sets for which certain infima are known to exist become especially interesting. For instance, a lattice is a partially ordered set in which all subsets have both a supremum and an infimum, and a complete lattice is a partially ordered set in which subsets have both a supremum and an infimum. More information on the various classes of partially ordered sets that arise from such considerations are found in the article on completeness properties.

If the supremum of a subset formula_1 exists, it is unique. If formula_1 contains a greatest element, then that element is the supremum; otherwise, the supremum does not belong to formula_1 (or does not exist). Likewise, if the infimum exists, it is unique. If formula_1 contains a least element, then that element is the infimum; otherwise, the infimum does not belong to formula_1 (or does not exist).

== Relation to maximum and minimum elements ==

The infimum of a subset formula_1 of a partially ordered set formula_31 assuming it exists, does not necessarily belong to formula_61 If it does, it is a minimum or least element of formula_61 Similarly, if the supremum of formula_1 belongs to formula_4 it is a maximum or greatest element of formula_61

For example, consider the set of negative real numbers (excluding zero). This set has no greatest element, since for every element of the set, there is another, larger, element. For instance, for any negative real number formula_66 there is another negative real number formula_67 which is greater. On the other hand, every real number greater than or equal to zero is certainly an upper bound on this set. Hence, formula_16 is the least upper bound of the negative reals, so the supremum is 0. This set has a supremum but no greatest element.

However, the definition of maximal and minimal elements is more general. In particular, a set can have many maximal and minimal elements, whereas infima and suprema are unique.

Whereas maxima and minima must be members of the subset that is under consideration, the infimum and supremum of a subset need not be members of that subset themselves.

=== Minimal upper bounds ===
Finally, a partially ordered set may have many minimal upper bounds without having a least upper bound. Minimal upper bounds are those upper bounds for which there is no strictly smaller element that also is an upper bound. This does not say that each minimal upper bound is smaller than all other upper bounds, it merely is not greater. The distinction between &quot;minimal&quot; and &quot;least&quot; is only possible when the given order is not a total one. In a totally ordered set, like the real numbers, the concepts are the same.

As an example, let formula_1 be the set of all finite subsets of natural numbers and consider the partially ordered set obtained by taking all sets from formula_1 together with the set of integers formula_71 and the set of positive real numbers formula_72 ordered by subset inclusion as above. Then clearly both formula_71 and formula_15 are greater than all finite sets of natural numbers. Yet, neither is formula_15 smaller than formula_71 nor is the converse true: both sets are minimal upper bounds but none is a supremum.

=== Least-upper-bound property ===
The is an example of the aforementioned completeness properties which is typical for the set of real numbers. This property is sometimes called .

If an ordered set formula_1 has the property that every nonempty subset of formula_1 having an upper bound also has a least upper bound, then formula_1 is said to have the least-upper-bound property. As noted above, the set formula_80 of all real numbers has the least-upper-bound property. Similarly, the set formula_71 of integers has the least-upper-bound property; if formula_1 is a nonempty subset of formula_71 and there is some number formula_84 such that every element formula_85 of formula_1 is less than or equal to formula_87 then there is a least upper bound formula_88 for formula_4 an integer that is an upper bound for formula_1 and is less than or equal to every other upper bound for formula_61 A well-ordered set also has the least-upper-bound property, and the empty subset has also a least upper bound: the minimum of the whole set.

An example of a set that the least-upper-bound property is formula_92 the set of rational numbers. Let formula_1 be the set of all rational numbers formula_94 such that formula_95 Then formula_1 has an upper bound (formula_97 for example, or formula_98) but no least upper bound in formula_99: If we suppose formula_100 is the least upper bound, a contradiction is immediately deduced because between any two reals formula_101 and formula_22 (including formula_103 and formula_104) there exists some rational formula_105 which itself would have to be the least upper bound (if formula_106) or a member of formula_1 greater than formula_104 (if formula_109). Another example is the hyperreals; there is no least upper bound of the set of positive infinitesimals.

There is a corresponding ; an ordered set possesses the greatest-lower-bound property if and only if it also possesses the least-upper-bound property; the least-upper-bound of the set of lower bounds of a set is the greatest-lower-bound, and the greatest-lower-bound of the set of upper bounds of a set is the least-upper-bound of the set.

If in a partially ordered set formula_2 every bounded subset has a supremum, this applies also, for any set formula_111 in the function space containing all functions from formula_112 to formula_31 where formula_114 if and only if formula_115 for all formula_116 For example, it applies for real functions, and, since these can be considered special cases of functions, for real formula_84-tuples and sequences of real numbers.

The least-upper-bound property is an indicator of the suprema.

