where the components formula_132 are antisymmetric in formula_133.

The corresponding transformation on spin space is
formula_134
This is an abuse of notation, but a standard one. The reason is formula_121 is not a well-defined function of formula_119, since there are two different sets of components formula_132 (up to equivalence) which give the same formula_119 but different formula_121. In practice we implicitly pick one of these formula_132 and then formula_121 is well defined in terms of formula_142

Under a Lorentz transformation, the Dirac equation
formula_143
becomes
formula_144

Associated to Lorentz invariance is a conserved Noether current, or rather a tensor of conserved Noether currents formula_145. Similarly, since the equation is invariant under translations, there is a tensor of conserved Noether currents formula_146, which can be identified as the stress-energy tensor of the theory. The Lorentz current formula_145 can be written in terms of the stress-energy tensor in addition to a tensor representing internal angular momentum.

==== Further discussion of Lorentz covariance of the Dirac equation====
The Dirac equation is Lorentz covariant. Articulating this helps illuminate not only the Dirac equation, but also the Majorana spinor and Elko spinor, which although closely related, have subtle and important differences.

Understanding Lorentz covariance is simplified by keeping in mind the geometric character of the process. Let formula_148 be a single, fixed point in the spacetime manifold. Its location can be expressed in multiple coordinate systems. In the physics literature, these are written as formula_149 and formula_150, with the understanding that both formula_149 and formula_150 describe &quot;the same&quot; point formula_148, but in different local frames of reference (a frame of reference over a small extended patch of spacetime). 
One can imagine formula_148 as having a fiber of different coordinate frames above it. In geometric terms, one says that spacetime can be characterized as a fiber bundle, and specifically, the frame bundle. The difference between two points formula_149 and formula_150 in the same fiber is a combination of rotations and Lorentz boosts. A choice of coordinate frame is a (local) section through that bundle.

Coupled to the frame bundle is a second bundle, the spinor bundle. A section through the spinor bundle is just the particle field (the Dirac spinor, in the present case). Different points in the spinor fiber correspond to the same physical object (the fermion) but expressed in different Lorentz frames. Clearly, the frame bundle and the spinor bundle must be tied together in a consistent fashion to get consistent results; formally, one says that the spinor bundle is the associated bundle; it is associated to a principal bundle, which in the present case is the frame bundle. Differences between points on the fiber correspond to the symmetries of the system. The spinor bundle has two distinct generators of its symmetries: the total angular momentum and the intrinsic angular momentum. Both correspond to Lorentz transformations, but in different ways.

The presentation here follows that of Itzykson and Zuber. It is very nearly identical to that of Bjorken and Drell. A similar derivation in a general relativistic setting can be found in Weinberg. Here we fix our spacetime to be flat, that is, our spacetime is Minkowski space.

Under a Lorentz transformation formula_157 the Dirac spinor to transform as
formula_158
It can be shown that an explicit expression for formula_159 is given by
formula_160
where formula_161 parameterizes the Lorentz transformation, and formula_162 are the six 4×4 matrices satisfying:
formula_163

This matrix can be interpreted as the intrinsic angular momentum of the Dirac field. That it deserves this interpretation arises by contrasting it to the generator formula_164 of Lorentz transformations, having the form
formula_165
This can be interpreted as the total angular momentum. It acts on the spinor field as
formula_166
Note the formula_149 above does &quot;not&quot; have a prime on it: the above is obtained by transforming formula_168 obtaining the change to formula_169 and then returning to the original coordinate system formula_170.

The geometrical interpretation of the above is that the frame field is affine, having no preferred origin. The generator formula_164 generates the symmetries of this space: it provides a relabelling of a fixed point formula_172 The generator formula_162 generates a movement from one point in the fiber to another: a movement from formula_168 with both formula_149 and formula_150 still corresponding to the same spacetime point formula_177 These perhaps obtuse remarks can be elucidated with explicit algebra.

Let formula_178 be a Lorentz transformation. The Dirac equation is
formula_179
If the Dirac equation is to be covariant, then it should have exactly the same form in all Lorentz frames:
formula_180
The two spinors formula_61 and formula_182 should both describe the same physical field, and so should be related by a transformation that does not change any physical observables (charge, current, mass, &quot;etc.&quot;) The transformation should encode only the change of coordinate frame. It can be shown that such a transformation is a 4×4 unitary matrix. Thus, one may presume that the relation between the two frames can be written as
formula_183
Inserting this into the transformed equation, the result is
formula_184
The coordinates related by Lorentz transformation satisfy: 
formula_185
The original Dirac equation is then regained if
formula_186
An explicit expression for formula_187 (equal to the expression given above) can be obtained by considering a Lorentz transformation of infinitesimal rotation near the identity transformation:
formula_188 
where formula_189 is the metric tensor : formula_190 and is symmetric while formula_191 is antisymmetric. After plugging and chugging, one obtains
formula_192
which is the (infinitesimal) form for formula_159 above and yields the relation formula_194 . To obtain the affine relabelling, write
formula_195

After properly antisymmetrizing, one obtains the generator of symmetries formula_164 given earlier. Thus, both formula_164 and formula_162 can be said to be the &quot;generators of Lorentz transformations&quot;, but with a subtle distinction: the first corresponds to a relabelling of points on the affine frame bundle, which forces a translation along the fiber of the spinor on the spin bundle, while the second corresponds to translations along the fiber of the spin bundle (taken as a movement formula_168 along the frame bundle, as well as a movement formula_200 along the fiber of the spin bundle.) Weinberg provides additional arguments for the physical interpretation of these as total and intrinsic angular momentum.

== Other formulations ==
The Dirac equation can be formulated in a number of other ways.

=== Curved spacetime ===

This article has developed the Dirac equation in flat spacetime according to special relativity. It is possible to formulate the Dirac equation in curved spacetime.

=== The algebra of physical space ===

This article developed the Dirac equation using four-vectors and Schrödinger operators. The Dirac equation in the algebra of physical space uses a Clifford algebra over the real numbers, a type of geometric algebra.

=== Coupled Weyl Spinors ===

As mentioned above, the &quot;massless&quot; Dirac equation immediately reduces to the homogeneous Weyl equation. By using the chiral representation of the gamma matrices, the nonzero-mass equation can also be decomposed into a pair of &quot;coupled&quot; inhomogeneous Weyl equations acting on the first and last pairs of indices of the original four-component spinor, i.e. formula_201, where formula_202 and formula_203 are each two-component Weyl spinors. This is because the skew block form of the chiral gamma matrices means that they swap the formula_202 and formula_203 and apply the two-by-two Pauli matrices to each:

formula_206.

So the Dirac equation

formula_207

becomes

formula_208

which in turn is equivalent to a pair of inhomogeneous Weyl equations for massless left- and right-helicity spinors, where the coupling strength is proportional to the mass:

formula_209

formula_210.

This has been proposed as an intuitive explanation of Zitterbewegung, as these massless components would propagate at the speed of light and move in opposite directions, since the helicity is the projection of the spin onto the direction of motion. Here the role of the &quot;mass&quot; formula_211 is not to make the velocity less than the speed of light, but instead controls the average rate at which these reversals occur; specifically, the reversals can be modeled as a Poisson process.

== U(1) symmetry ==
Natural units are used in this section. The coupling constant is labelled by convention with formula_212: this parameter can also be viewed as modelling the electron charge.

=== Vector symmetry ===
The Dirac equation and action admits a formula_58 symmetry where the fields formula_214 transform as
formula_215
This is a global symmetry, known as the formula_58 vector symmetry (as opposed to the formula_58 axial symmetry: see below). By Noether&#x27;s theorem there is a corresponding conserved current: this has been mentioned previously as
formula_218

=== Gauging the symmetry ===

If we &#x27;promote&#x27; the global symmetry, parametrised by the constant formula_219, to a local symmetry, parametrised by a function formula_220, or equivalently formula_221 the Dirac equation is no longer invariant: there is a residual derivative of formula_222.

The fix proceeds as in scalar electrodynamics: the partial derivative is promoted to a covariant derivative formula_223
formula_224
formula_225
The covariant derivative depends on the field being acted on. The newly introduced formula_226 is the 4-vector potential from electrodynamics, but also can be viewed as a formula_58 gauge field (which, mathematically, is defined as a formula_58 connection).

The transformation law under gauge transformations for formula_226 is then the usual
formula_230
but can also be derived by asking that covariant derivatives transform under a gauge transformation as
formula_231
formula_232
We then obtain a gauge-invariant Dirac action by promoting the partial derivative to a covariant one:
formula_233
The final step needed to write down a gauge-invariant Lagrangian is to add a Maxwell Lagrangian term,
formula_234
Putting these together gives
 = \int d^4x\,\left[-\frac{1}{4}F^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu} + \bar\psi\,(iD\!\!\!\!\big / - m)\,\psi\right]&lt;/math&gt;
