=== Axial symmetry ===
Massless Dirac fermions, that is, fields formula_80 satisfying the Dirac equation with formula_57, admit a second, inequivalent formula_58 symmetry.

This is seen most easily by writing the four-component Dirac fermion formula_80 as a pair of two-component vector fields,
formula_240
and adopting the chiral representation for the gamma matrices, so that formula_241 may be written
formula_242
where formula_243 has components formula_244 and formula_245 has components formula_246.

The Dirac action then takes the form
formula_247
That is, it decouples into a theory of two Weyl spinors or Weyl fermions.

The earlier vector symmetry is still present, where formula_248 and formula_249 rotate identically. This form of the action makes the second inequivalent formula_58 symmetry manifest:
formula_251
This can also be expressed at the level of the Dirac fermion as 
formula_252
where formula_253 is the exponential map for matrices.

This isn&#x27;t the only formula_58 symmetry possible, but it is conventional. Any &#x27;linear combination&#x27; of the vector and axial symmetries is also a formula_58 symmetry.

Classically, the axial symmetry admits a well-formulated gauge theory. But at the quantum level, there is an anomaly, that is, an obstruction to gauging.

=== Extension to color symmetry ===

We can extend this discussion from an abelian formula_58 symmetry to a general non-abelian symmetry under a gauge group formula_257, the group of color symmetries for a theory.

For concreteness, we fix formula_258, the special unitary group of matrices acting on formula_259.

Before this section, formula_80 could be viewed as a spinor field on Minkowski space, in other words a function formula_261, and its components in formula_62 are labelled by spin indices, conventionally Greek indices taken from the start of the alphabet formula_263.

Promoting the theory to a gauge theory, informally formula_61 acquires a part transforming like formula_259, and these are labelled by color indices, conventionally Latin indices formula_266. In total, formula_80 has formula_268 components, given in indices by formula_269. The &#x27;spinor&#x27; labels only how the field transforms under spacetime transformations.

Formally, formula_80 is valued in a tensor product, that is, it is a function formula_271

Gauging proceeds similarly to the abelian formula_58 case, with a few differences. Under a gauge transformation formula_273 the spinor fields transform as
formula_274
formula_275
The matrix-valued gauge field formula_226 or formula_277 connection transforms as
formula_278
and the covariant derivatives defined 
formula_279
formula_280
transform as 
formula_281
formula_282

Writing down a gauge-invariant action proceeds exactly as with the formula_58 case, replacing the Maxwell Lagrangian with the Yang–Mills Lagrangian
formula_284
where the Yang–Mills field strength or curvature is defined here as
formula_285
and formula_286 is the matrix commutator.

The action is then
 = \int d^4x\,\left[-\frac{1}{4}\text{Tr}(F^{\mu\nu}F_{\mu\nu}) + \bar\psi\,(iD\!\!\!\!\big / - m)\,\psi\right]&lt;/math&gt;
|border
|border colour =#50C878
|background colour = #ECFCF4

==== Physical applications ====
For physical applications, the case formula_287 describes the quark sector of the Standard Model which models strong interactions. Quarks are modelled as Dirac spinors; the gauge field is the gluon field. The case formula_288 describes part of the electroweak sector of the Standard Model. Leptons such as electrons and neutrinos are the Dirac spinors; the gauge field is the formula_289 gauge boson.

==== Generalisations ====
This expression can be generalised to arbitrary Lie group formula_257 with connection formula_226 and a representation formula_292, where the colour part of formula_61 is valued in formula_294. Formally, the Dirac field is a function formula_295

Then formula_61 transforms under a gauge transformation formula_297 as
formula_298
and the covariant derivative is defined
formula_299
where here we view formula_300 as a Lie algebra representation of the Lie algebra formula_301 associated to formula_257.

This theory can be generalised to curved spacetime, but there are subtleties which arise in gauge theory on a general spacetime (or more generally still, a manifold) which, on flat spacetime, can be ignored. This is ultimately due to the contractibility of flat spacetime which allows us to view a gauge field and gauge transformations as defined globally on formula_63.

